From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: ask2 PR14z19 <ask2@local>
Date: Sat, 23 May 2026 05:50:00 +0000
Subject: fman_pcd: cc_node_remove_key() + cc_nodes debugfs view

PR14z19 Path A patch 0045 (third of three patches in the series).

Adds the public fman_pcd_cc_node_remove_key() ABI -- the tombstone-
idiom counterpart of fman_pcd_cc_node_add_key() that ASK2 needs to
retire individual flow rows without teardown-then-rebuild churn and
without losing slot-index stability (required for flow-id round-
tripping per plans/PR14z19-PATH-A-DESIGN.md sec 3.5).

Also adds the cc_nodes debugfs view alongside the kg_schemes / port_sp
views from patch 0046, so operators can visually inspect CC-tree /
CC-node layout in MURAM at any time including under load.  Non-
destructive (read-only struct walk, no register I/O); safe to cat
during traffic.

Files touched:
 * drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/fman/fman_pcd_cc.c
     - new fman_pcd_cc_node_remove_key() body
     - new fman_pcd_cc_nodes_dump_seq() same-module helper
 * drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/fman/fman_pcd.c
     - new cc_nodes debugfs show fn + debugfs_create_file()
 * drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/fman/fman_pcd_internal.h
     - prototype for fman_pcd_cc_nodes_dump_seq()
 * include/linux/fsl/fman_pcd.h
     - public prototype + kerneldoc for fman_pcd_cc_node_remove_key()
       (this file already carried the prototype before 0045 was
       split out; the chunk here is a no-op against the in-tree
       state when stacked on top of 0044)

Tombstone semantics:
  - AD slot is re-encoded as FMAN_PCD_ACTION_DROP (fqid=0 bypass,
    traps as invalid-FQ in DPAA1 if the walker ever reaches it).
  - Mask half of the match slot is zeroed so the walker skips this
    row for every possible extract value.
  - Key bytes are intentionally LEFT INTACT so cc_nodes debugfs
    dumps still show what USED to be at this index after a flow
    eviction storm (forensic-residue diagnosis).
  - num_keys is NOT decremented -- the slot remains live in
    indexing terms; only node_destroy() reclaims it.


